AGI - Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida asked for a meeting with Kim Jong Un>. Kim's sister reported it, adding that any vis a vis is unlikely to change the political line from Tokyo. "Kishida has recently expressed his desire to meet the President of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea's State Affairs Commission as soon as possible," said Kim Yo Jong> in a statement reported by the official Korean Central News Agency.
&nbsp;
Japanese Prime Minister Fumio Kishida called "important" high-level talks with North Korea, after Kim Jong Un's powerful sister reported Kishida's request for a two-point summit.
&nbsp;
"For relations between Japan and North Korea, high-level talks are important to solve issues such as kidnapping," said Kishida in parliament, referring to the abductions in the 1970s and 1980s. "For this reason, as I have already said in the past, we have embarked on several 'approaches' with North Korea directly under my control"

