AGI - Two Russian landing ships were attacked by Ukrainian forces in the Crimean Peninsula. Kiev sources have announced that they have hit "successfully" the ships "Yamal" and "Azov" during a bombing against the port of Sebastopoli and bombed also a center of communication and several infrastructures of the Russian fleet of the Black Sea.
&nbsp;
"It was the most massive attack in recent times," acknowledged the governor of Sebastopoli, Mikhail Razvojaiev, referring to a dead and four wounded.<br> Shared images on social media show a great explosion in the city, which generated a column of black smoke, and those that seemed to be Russian air defenses intercepting bullets.
&nbsp;
Ukraine claims to have destroyed about a third of the Russian Black Sea fleet since the beginning of the war, usually with night attacks with naval drones loaded with explosives.
&nbsp;
Satellite images show that Russia has moved much of the fleet to the east, towards the port of Novorosiisk. Also the capital of Ukraine and the western region of Lviv have undergone "massive" Russian bombing in the early hours of Sunday.
&nbsp;
The Ukrainian air force reported that Russia launched 29 cruise missiles and 28 drones and managed to break down 18 missiles and 25 drones.&nbsp; The governor of the Lviv region, Maksim Kozitski, reported missile attacks in the Stryi district, south of the city of Lviv.
&nbsp;
The Russian Ministry of Defence declared on Sunday that it launched a "collective attack" against Ukrainian military and energy objectives. "All the targets of the attack were affected," he said, claiming to have hit weapons factories.
&nbsp;
In Poland, the operating command of the armed forces reported that at night "an intense activity of long-range aircraft from the Russian Federation was observed and all the necessary procedures were activated to ensure the security of Polish air space".
&nbsp;
Later, the Polish army reported that for about forty seconds "the Polish airspace was violated by one of the cruise missiles launched tonight by the Russian Federation's aviation". "The object flew in the Polish space near the village of Oserdow and stayed there for 39 seconds," he added, underlining that the missile was monitored by military radar throughout the duration of the flight.
&nbsp;
Poland, which is a member of NATO, said it would ask Moscow to explain the incident. In December another similar incident occurred, when a Russian missile entered the Polish airspace and left it a few minutes later, heading to Ukraine.&nbsp;

